<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,310,1229,1255]" box="[189,310,1229,1255]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1229,1255]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" reason="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1229,1255]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[189,1399,1276,1795]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Small spiders. Prosoma longer than abdomen and broader behind PLEs. Anterior portion Fat, extending over 75–87% of prosomal length, posterior much steeper and slightly truncated (
<bibRefCitation author="Proszynski J." box="[1180,1387,1311,1337]" journalOrPublisher="Annales Zoologici" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 180" part="53" refString="Proszynski J. 2003. Salticidae (Araneae) of the Levant. Annales Zoologici 53: 1 - 180." title="Salticidae (Araneae) of the Levant" type="journal article" year="2003">Prószyński 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Short eye Feld. Third eye row located on the edges of prosoma. Chelicerae with two teeth on promargin and single bicuspid tooth on retromargin. Abdomen rounded or oval in shape, narrower than prosoma, with a pair of large white spots and chevrons posteriorly (
<bibRefCitation author="Proszynski J." box="[894,1098,1417,1443]" journalOrPublisher="Annales Zoologici" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 180" part="53" refString="Proszynski J. 2003. Salticidae (Araneae) of the Levant. Annales Zoologici 53: 1 - 180." title="Salticidae (Araneae) of the Levant" type="journal article" year="2003">Prószyński 2003</bibRefCitation>
), fused medially in most species, dorsal view of cymbium with large, round spot of white scales (
<figureCitation box="[1078,1152,1452,1478]" captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[220,1359,690,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[220,1359,690,1888]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Live specimens of Bristowia Reimoser, 1934 and Habrocestum Simon, 1876. A – B. B. gandhii sp. nov., ♀ from IFS Arboretum, Dambulla (IFS _ SAL 543). C – D. H. kodigalaensis sp. nov., Ƌ from Ritigala SNR, Kodigala, Sri Lanka (IFS _ SAL 516)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3228094/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
<collectionCode box="[1152,1174,1452,1478]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">C</collectionCode>
). Third and fourth legs longer (tibia plus patella 
<collectionCode box="[537,566,1488,1514]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">III</collectionCode>
± tibia plus patella 
<collectionCode box="[798,832,1488,1514]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">IV</collectionCode>
), femora III longer than others (
<bibRefCitation author="Richman D. B." box="[1207,1386,1487,1513]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="197 - 206" part="170" refString="Richman D. B. 1981. A Revision of the Genus Habrocestum (Araneae, Salticidae) in North America. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 170: 197 - 206." title="A Revision of the Genus Habrocestum (Araneae, Salticidae) in North America" type="journal article" year="1981">Richman 1981</bibRefCitation>
). Palp with single tibial apophysis which is hook shaped in most species. Bulbus elongated. Shape of embolus species speciFc, variable in length and originating under the tegulum. Conductor present or absent (
<bibRefCitation author="Wunderlich J." box="[278,488,1593,1619]" journalOrPublisher="Beitrage zur Araneologie" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="698 - 719" part="5" refString="Wunderlich J. 2008. IdentiFcation key to the European genera of the jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae). Beitrage zur Araneologie 5: 698 - 719." title="IdentiFcation key to the European genera of the jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae)" type="journal article" year="2008">Wunderlich 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Epigynum with small pocket-like sclerotized vaginal roof and shallow notch at posterior edge near epigastric furrow. Copulatory openings large, located laterally along the midlength of epigyne. Large, transverse and membranous white “window”, with translucent dark internal structures, very complicated consisting of large channels running anteriorly and then reversing back, passing into spermathecae with thick walls connected by soft channels (
<bibRefCitation author="Proszynski J." box="[1021,1222,1734,1760]" journalOrPublisher="Annales Zoologici" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 180" part="53" refString="Proszynski J. 2003. Salticidae (Araneae) of the Levant. Annales Zoologici 53: 1 - 180." title="Salticidae (Araneae) of the Levant" type="journal article" year="2003">Prószyński 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Some species with distinct accessory glands. Fertilization ducts narrow, originating from top of receptacles.
</paragraph>
